,Recommended,247080,32860049,Posted: 27 June,all,NEQSIS,"Crypt of the Necrodancer is absolutely fantastic, and a no-brainer to pick up when it's on sale (Steam Summer Sale, 80% off at $2.99).  Even still, at the regular price this game is definitely worth picking up.What is Necrodancer?Crypt of the Necrodancer is an old-school Zelda style dungeon crawler (think, A Link to the Past) that requires the player to take on challenging dungeons and bosses to progress through the game.  What sets it apart from any other games is its use of a music/rhythm mechanic for movement; you can only move one ""block"" of space at a time along with the beat of the games soundtrack (or your own music, if you want to use a custom soundtrack!).  Moving constantly with the beat and not taking damage from enemies builds your gold multiplier, allowing you to get more gold for character upgrades, items, and weapons to use through your run.  Stop moving to the beat, make a wrong move (i.e. jumping into a wall/trap) or take a hit, and your multiplier resets.  Does the rhythm movement mechanic seem gimmicky?  Not to worry, it's incredibly fun and the phenominal soundtrack makes for a great experience.  Custom soundtrack options are also great; the auto-beat-importer works very well, and if necessary you can create custom beats for any songs you import.Combat and WeaponsCombat in Necrodancer is fast and incredibly fun.  There's no ""attack wildly and pray for success"" here; successful combat requires deliberate and calculated attacks/movement.  In addition to the fun beat mechanic, weapon variability is what makes Necrodancer so fun and engaging.  Weapons vary greatly in attack types, range, buffs (i.e. knockback, freezing, etc.), and strength.  Certain weapons will definitely be more successful against some enemies than others, and your preference will largely depend on the play style you prefer.In addition to combat, the other two mechanics you'll consider are digging (via your shovel) and vision.  A large part of dungeons is finding your way around, digging up ""diamonds"" to use for permanent upgrades and other unlockables, and finding hidden rooms for temporary items or character buffs.  Both your shovel and vision (view distance) can be upgraded to allow more efficient exploration and finding better items for your runs.Runs last until you complete the dungeon and move on to the next, die, or the level's song ends (~5 minutes) and kicks you to the next level of the dungeon automatically (but, if you dont find the exit and the level auto-ends, you lose your score multiplier).ProgressionProgression in Necrodancer is very difficult, but fair and rewards mastering the movement/beat mechanic.  Learning enemy and boss attack patters is paramount to success, and enemies very greatly from level to level and present a great challenge as you progress.Each time you die you are returned to a lobby where you can buy upgrades for your character to improve for your next run.  You can only spend ""diamonds"" in the lobby earned from your immediate previous run, and starting a new one resets all of your ""diamonds"" that can be spent in the lobby.  With a variety of dungeons, bosses and increasing difficulty as you progress you'll definitely get some good (and fun) play time out of this game.  There are also a large variety of different playable characters that change game mechanics and add tons of play time and very high replay value.  For example, the ""Bard"" can move freely (is unlocked from the beat mechanic), but every time you move functions as a ""beat"" in the game - so as you move, enemies move, and the faster you move, the faster they move, and the faster you move, the faster the timer for the level expires still requiring you to be deliberate in movement.Verdict: Absolutely recommend, 8/10, one of the best casual, low-commitment games I've played in a very, very long time."
