76561198021263677,Not Recommended,247080,23697726,"Posted: 21 June, 2016",all,evan.scott,"There are quite a few things to like about Crypt of the NecroDancer, and there's no question that it is the result of having an interesting crazy idea and running with it - and I love seeing game writers taking risks and doing crazy interesting stuff.But.  This just doesn't work for me.  I'm probably not really the target audience - I have never gotten into the rhythm/dance games at all, and am now probably a bit old and just not generally able to slip into the ""zone"" when playing.Playing the game 'properly', with the beat (not as Bard) is frequently just too chaotic and confusing - particularly when starting out with this constant time pressure (not just the urgency of keeping to the beat, but also knowing there's only a limited amount of time until the song ends and you get forcibly moved on).  I frequently couldn't work out what items were - reading the text was problematic at times, and if I'd picked something up that I didn't already know I found it quite difficult to work out what I had picked up and what to do with it.Playing as Bard (not the default for a Newbie, and I understand why because it doesn't really represent the 'core experience' of the game) sort of solved a lot of this - the time pressure is removed so you can spend as long as you need to look at items and play around with them and learn the enemy behaviour.  But playing as Bard is just dull for the most part.  Removing that core mechanic does drain the game of any particular interest.  I thought it would make sense to play as Bard enough to learn what I needed to learn and then go back in with the beat to enjoy the game, but frankly it just didn't hold enough appeal to do this.The music is great.  The graphics are ok.  The roguelike stuff is ok, although the upgrade system is a bit thin, a bit poorly implemented and a bit ... I don't know, just patchy.  Not enough richness to make it feel worth crawling through the dungeon again and again like a good dungeon crawler does.And there are bugs.  Playing on Windows it just dumped me out of the game every other hour or so.  Not such a big deal, but not great.  And a few possibly deliberate gameplay choices that seem like bugs - the mimics that reveal themselves when you stand next to them, but are still counted as ""fail"" moves to attack until you take a step and get them to move off their square.  It's sitting right there pulsating, I know I need to kill it, but you just fail me for swinging at it?  Minor, but annoying nonetheless.I think there are people who will enjoy this, but it frustrated me too often for too little reward and too little motivation to keep playing."
