76561197992763328,Recommended,247080,24503112,"Posted: 24 July, 2016",all,Ivanthecur,"This game is easily my favorite game of 2016.  The soundtrack is amazing which is important since you'll be using the audio cues for movement.  When buying the game, I assumed I would want to play with my own mp3s.  That is absolutely not the case (I cannot stress enough how well crafted the music is).  The four zone bosses are awesome and unique with their own soundtrack that matches their theme.  The difficulty curve is perfect.  Once you start to master a zone, you move to the next zone and are immediately given a healthy dose of humility as the basic enemies brutalize you and it's time to learn brand new enemy patterns all over again.  Because of the diamond upgrade system you don't feel bad for dying and it keeps the items you find in chests less complex until you master them and are ready for shiny new spells/weapons/stuff.  Because the levels are random, they never get boring or predictable.  And here's the real kicker.  Each different character you unlock has a different playstyle which changes how you play the levels completely.  I recently found out that some characters have different remixes of the standard songs too which is amazing.Honestly, I cannot recommend this game enough.  If you enjoy a challange and like dungeon exploration games that require you to think rather than level stats, this game is for you."
,Recommended,247080,15512182,"Posted: 23 April, 2015",all,Azure,"Rhythm games and dungeon crawlers seem like they'd be incompatible, but Crypt of the NecroDancer makes the two work together. You have to move and act to the beat of the music, so you must assess the enemies, traps, and walls around you and act very quickly. The enemies start out simple enough, with easy-to-tell movement patterns. However, subsequent zones become muh trickier, with things and foes that mess with your position or require you to be very attentive of your surroundings. Managing and understanding is key in reaching the end of the game.There are a fair amount of extras here. In your regular runs you collect diamonds, which you use to unlock new items to find in your runs, upgrades like more life or a higher money multiplier, the opportunity to practice against bosses, and more. There are several different characters to play as, who all change the game in some manner, which can be as simple as requiring you to act in double time or as substantial as restricting your weaponry to bombs.The music is fantastic. As you may expect from the title, it's all very dancable stuff. I seriously would listen to this at a party. Perhaps the best part is the various ways it's mixed when you enter certain areas. The graphics are in a pixel style and it looks and animates well enough.In summary, Crypt of the NecroDancer takes rhythm and dungeon crawling elements together and brings out the best of both of them. Combine that with a great soundtrack, and the end result is a game that comes highly recommended.Also, NecroDancer is a superb pun. I mean, it's simple and thematically appropriate!"
