,Recommended,247080,27671638,"Posted: 26 November, 2016",all,NBlast,"EVERYBODY DO THE FLOP!After the unfair atrocity against humanity that is Spelunky, I jumped away from the rouge-lite bandwagon and started to avoid this kind of games entirely. You cannot imagine the frustration which that cursed game gave me with its extreme unpredictability of annoying enemies, dirt-poor and mostly useless item pool, random stuff blowing up in your face without your fault etc.Good thing that Crypt of the Necrodancer fixes nearly everything I listed above. Listening to the Overwhelmingly Positive rating on Steam apparently is sometimes a good idea!You can imagine the game as a mix of classic dungeon-crawling games, generic rouge-lite games, chess and DanceDance Revolution. During the proper gameplay player makes moves on tiled dungeons, trying to move, attack, defend, explore and explode to the bounce of the sickest beats. You can consider beats as a split-second turns when everybody on the level makes their action and the outcome is immediately apparent. Either you move into enemy-infested tile and attack it or they move into yours, dealing damage etc. Every action in the game is bound to the beat of boogey-man looking Necrodancer who is the main villain of this really barebones and after-thought of the story.CotN fixes EVERYTHING Spelunky screwed up. Aside of non-common bat types, every enemy has a predicable pattern you can exploit. Items you acquire throughout your adventure are varied, allowing different playstyles and strategies. There is not nigh-required Jet-Pack and Shotgun combo you need in Spelunky because in Necrodancer many combinations of items can ease the difficulty significantly. Game also doesn't screw you up unfairly too often. Most of the time you lose because of your own mistakes and not because somebody else angered the shopkeeper or that Yeti made a bouncing ping-pong ball of you, sapping your whole life in the process. You are still fragile in the game, but healing is much less a pain-in-the-butt process andit's much more reliable. Crypt still has some fair share of annoying enemies but those are much more manageable than in the other rouge-lites. There are also single-level modes (allows story progression with checkpoints between zones) and additional, harder characters, so both less-hardcores and harder that hard-hardcores are welcomed here.As for problems of the NecroDancer: bats still exist. Enemies sometimes come in crowds, making difficulty in tackling them safely. Item descriptions are vague and show up only when you approach them from tile away, from which you need to jump off immediately, forcing you to needless experimentation until you memorize the effects. Level themes are extremely generic (Mine/Forest/Ice-Fire World/Temple) which is a missed opportunity in comparison to the rest of the game (like enemies which are really imaginative with bouncy and enjoyable animations and charm).In short, Crypt of the Necrodancer in an enchanting game, full of enjoyable gameplay, good inventive ideas and incredible music (which really goes without saying that loud. Bought the soundtracks... All of them). It's must-have on the nearest occasion for everybody who isn't tone-deaf, without the sense of rhythm or satisfaction from fair challenge.Also, f*** Spelunky."
