,Recommended,247080,12979107,"Posted: 17 November, 2014",all,Ocelost,"Unexpectedly Brilliant!I had been browsing Steam for at least an hour, looking for something that might hold my interest for more than a few minutes. By the time this game turned up, I was not very hopeful. The gloomy title conjured up images of a tedious slog through yet another Tolkein knock-off world. The screenshots reminded me of a hundred junk titles that bill themselves as ""retro"" and ""8-bit"" to lure long-time gamers into parting with their money in a quest to recapture good memories from their childhood. The description, touting the unlikely fusion of roguelike and rhythm genres, left me almost certain that this was nothing more than a concept gimmick that would fail to meet even the lowest of expectations.I could not have been more wrong.Crypt of the NecroDancer is the most inspired, refreshing contribution to gaming that I have encountered in years. This game blends the simplest and most predictable mechanics with enough variety to be challenging and so much creativity that even casual players will have a whole lot of goofy fun. I've played countless times over the past few weeks, died in most of them, and found myself smiling anyway, because it was almost always my own fault rather than the result of an impossible situation or bad user interface, and because it's easy to jump right back in.Each creature has a specific pattern of movement with consistent restrictions, and is easily identifiable on sight, so you can usually predict what it will do next. It will always move on the beat of the music. Press one of the four direction buttons, and you'll move, interact with an obstacle, or attack an enemy in that direction. Do it on the beat, or you'll be sorry. Use items from your inventory by pressing two buttons at once. Following these rules, you'll find yourself learning the patterns of movement (or dances) required to subdue each monster and make your way deeper into the dungeon.On top of that solid foundation sits a cast of unique bosses, playable characters with different abilities, unlockable upgrades, training areas, cooperative mode, instant replays, a level editor, gamepad and dance mat support, cross-platform compatibility, a surprisingly good chiptune-style soundtrack, and the ability to import whatever music your dungeon-crawling heart desires.And it's still only an alpha.Outstanding work, Brace Yourself Games. You shattered the preconceptions of this linux-using nethack fan. Now take my money."
76561197972321908,Recommended,247080,19914697,"Posted: 24 December, 2015",all,zyl0x,"Fun, original, and imaginative take on the Gauntlet-styled dungeon-crawler. As you can guess from the trailers (and title), NecroDancer is a brilliant twist on the ""keep-the-beat"" music games such as Guitar Hero, Elite Beat, and Dance Dance. The graphics are nice and clean. Enemies are well-designed. Levels are procedurally generated ala Diablo, but are small enough that you don't ever feel frustrated or lost. The game has a very gradual difficulty curve that starts out easy but can become quite challenging. There are many different characters to unlock with their own playstyles and challenges, including a class that doesn't even have to keep the beat at all, for those of you who would like to just play at your own tempo (or have a poor sense of musical timing.)The highlight of the game is of course the absolutely fantastic soundtrack, but even if you're not a fan of the music itself, you can just set up your own playlist and play along with whatever music you like.I very strongly recommend this game at any price point!"
