76561198036212216,Recommended,247080,12274715,"Posted: 28 September, 2014",all,Ameretat,"Litterally the first words I thought to myself after quitting my first stint of this game? ""Wow, that was actually really good.""Perhaps not the most insightful of comments, but I MEANT it, and this was a surprising fact. Looking at the game on steam, you may think ""So a rogue-like with music. Right"" And technically, you'd be right. But that's like calling a burger ""cows backside with month old milk covered on top""It just doesn't do it justice.The gameplay is what you'd expect from the genre, constant paranoia of the simplest mobs knowing they could end your playthrough merely by invading your personal space. However, the twist is, they are all 100% predictable. Green slimes don't move. Blue ones bounce in a grid, one square per beat. Minotaurs charge in a straight line until they hit a wall, dragons...well, I still have yet to work that one out. But dragons hurt, and I don't like them anymore.You yourself are 'constrained' by the rules as well. If YOU don't move to the beat (which I have to admit, is catchy) you'll lose your coin multiplier bonus. That's it, nothing 'life ending' but...it makes it harder, thus worthwhile. *This is only valid if you don't play the bard character, who has different rules I won't go into*The rest? Eh, the graphics are bright, but still suit the 'dark' theme. Sort of like a Scooby Doo episode. The sound I was shocked with (In a good way) and the gameplay...well, I'm eager to go back for more.Once I forget about the dragons, that is.8.5/10, with only the 'promise for more' alpha state on it preventing it from getting higher (Can you rate an unfinished game as perfect?)Would highly recommend to any fans of the genre."
