76561198032943425,Recommended,247080,12872314,"Posted: 9 November, 2014",all,VectorX,"I'll admit, I was a bit skeptical of this game when I first started.  I loved DDR and I love roguelikes, but to mix the two?  What fresh madness was this?  THIS WAS THE EPIC MUSIC MADNESS OF THE DEEP!  The music is energetic and fun, the game is easy to learn and the tutorial is short (seriously, VERY short, but all you need to know).The game is most certainly a roguelike, no saves, randomized layouts and drops.  But that's just the beginning.  Your ability to sync your movements to the beat isn't just a gimmick.  This mechanic rewards you with things like coin bonuses for the long combos you can create as you dance through the levels.  It requires you to plan while you move, if you stop, you miss a beat and you lose your combo.The game is simple and addicting.  You never feel too bad about dying because you use the rewards you gained from the previous play to help you on your next, simply perpetuating your endless jimmy through the dark tunnels as you slay monsters with  your dance moves and your beat only legend can recount.A bit pricey at $15.  I bought it on sale and it was well worth the money.  If you love roguelikes and love awesome soundtracks, it could very well be worth the money.  If you're on the fence, wait for a sale and jump on the deal like Jon Travolta on a disco beat."
,Recommended,247080,14148286,"Posted: 24 January, 2015",all,하나님,Absolutely love the beat and the mechanics of the game are superb and challenging nuff' said
,Recommended,247080,19504441,"Posted: 5 December, 2015",all,Ksempac,"Crypt of the Necrodancer is about delving into a dungeon, but you're doing so in synch with the current's level music : every action you take must be on the beat, any missed beat is slightly penalized, and enemies also move on the beat.Yet, to call Crypt of the Necrodancer ""dungeon delving with music"" would be to sell it short. A far better description would be ""tactical turn-based game, except the turns happen on the beat"". Crypt of the Necrodancer has you dancing around monsters in order to kill everything while taking as little damage as possible. You know all the monsters' patterns, there is no luck involved, it's just a matter of perfecting your counter patterns. Even the music aspect has been toned down a bit to ensure you focus more on the tactical aspect: the game doesn't require pinpoint accuracy to hit the beat, there is a fair beat of leaway, contrary to games that are purely about hitting beats (such as Dance Dance Revolution, Osu, etc...).The best example of how the game isn't just a ""game with a music gimmick"" is the ""Bard"" character. Once you've played a bit, you will unlock new characters, which are new modes of play. And Bard's mode is actually being able to play without having to worry about the beat: whenever you take an action, the ennemies do too, which mean you can play as fast or as slow as you want. And yet, despite not being time-pressured, it's still a fair and interesting challenge to play and finish a Bard's playthrough.The game is hard, but is also very fair. As I said, everything is known, and the game lobby offers several ways to train yourself and gather informations on enemies in a stressless manner. So after that, once you think you've learned everything you needed, you can delve into the musical dungeon, and then all hell break loose. You know skeletons raise theirs arms before moving, and yet, in the stress of having to move constantly, you keep moving towards skeletons with raised arms, and then getting damaged. It's going to take a lot of practice to become good and finish the game.But well, practicing is so much fun in this game. The graphics are great, with cute zombies dancing around, skeletons swaying their hips while moving towards you, etc. All the characters have very nicely done animations and attention to details. It also has good replayability, thanks to the randomly generated dungeons and items. Each weapon has its own strenghs and weaknesses and really change how you're going to approach each ennemy. And finally the last, but greatest element...the music.The OST for this game has been done by none other than Danny Baranowsky, one of the most famous guy in the small world of indie video game music. If you've played Super Meat Boy, Desktop Dungeons, Canabalt, or the Binding of Isaac, you already know how awesome his music is. If you don't i highly recommend checking its music on Bandcamp. I actually bought Crypt of the Necrodancer's OST months before actually buying the game. Each track is a marvel, each world has its own music soundscape, and there is a lot of music-related surprise to find while playing the game.TLDR : This game is awesome, if you like hard tactical games, buy it, and also buy the soundtrack on Bandcamp :)"
76561198046533401,Recommended,247080,15706661,"Posted: 5 May, 2015",all,primoaurelius,"freaking amazing concept. a dancy roguelike. custom music and mods adds an amazing amount to the game. even music that you think might not sound right, ends up being really fun to play along to. however, this doesnt mean that the music that is provided is bad, because its not. the 2 or 3 OSTs that are provided are really awesome as well, with an electronic/dance feel to them. each and every enemy has its own individual pattern that you can learn to help you devise tactics to stay alive, but you have to think quick to keep up with the beat. items, spells, and weapons of all kinds are used and found  throughout the game to take on enemies in new and different ways. highly recommend it for its originality."
