,Recommended,247080,12296670,"Posted: 29 September, 2014",all,Feeble,"Crypt of the NecroDancer is a dungeon - crawler with rogue - like elements... Yeah, I know. Go ahead. Sigh if you want to. It's okay. I'll wait.Yes, it's true. We're currently in a market hugely oversaturated with ""dungeon-crawling roguelike"" titles. But unlike many other games of its genre, NecroDancer manages to stand out and hold its own with its unique and very fun spin on the familiar idea.The premise is simple enough. You enter the first floor of a procedurally-generated dungeon, moving in four cardinal directions, fighting various monsters and finding random treasure items such as weapons, armor, spells and consumables. On each floor of the dungeon there's a shopkeeper you can do business with.Sounds very familiar, right? Well this is where NecroDancer does things differently. Everything you do in the dungeon, such as moving, fighting, using items, and digging through walls... you have to synchronize with the beat of the music. All of the enemies follow this rule too, and as a result you have a system that's fairly easy to pick up and very satisfying to master and tinker with. On your first few runs you'll be so concerned with keeping the beat that you'll just throw yourself headfirst into enemies and traps, but you'll soon improve the point where timing yourself and enemies is second nature, and you'll beat the boss... only to have this cycle repeat itself in the new area you've unlocked. The game has a short and simple tutorial that explains how to play, but you'll have to learn the rest for yourself.Each run of the game gives you a newly generated layout, but between runs you have a sort of hub where you can unlock upgrades (very similar to something like Rogue Legacy), change characters, and train against monsters and bosses. Additionally, there's a daily challenge dungeon available to everyone.Music-wise, each floor of the dungeon has its own BGM. You can set the music to any MP3 you have on your computer (which works very well), but I kept going back to the original music because it's awesome. The default BGM fits the game perfectly.NecroDancer has full controller support, but doesn't really explain it. If you're using a 360 controller like I am, Use (A, B, X, and Y) to move in their respective cardinal directions. This applies to menus too, with B as confirm and X as back. My one qualm with this game so far is this somewhat awkward menu control.Overall, I would highly recommend Crypt of the NecroDancer to anyone. Whether you're a big fan of the genre or just someone looking for a fun title, it has something for you. NecroDancer is definitely worth its price tag.P.S.It's only in alpha and it's already this goodIt made it out of early accessP.P.S. Do I even need to mention the awesome cheesy pun in the title?P.P.P.S. You can even hook this game up to a USB dance pad, like something you'd use to play Dance Dance Revolution. I don't have one, and even if I did I'm far too lazy / would probably have a heart attack if I tried but STILL. YOU CAN DO THAT."
