76561197972411061,Recommended,247080,19963997,"Posted: 26 December, 2015",all,Samantha :],"Crypt of the NecroDancer is a dungeon-crawler game set to the beat of music. The game is divided into 4 zones with several levels in each zone. In each level you must use your arrow keys to move your character in time beat of the music, the longer you can keep in time, the larger bonsues you can get which result in increased gold drops from enemies you defeat. At the end of the song, you are automatically dropped to the next level (or zone boss if you're on the last level of the zone) or you can procede to the next level by finding the stairs which may need to be opened by defeating a tougher enemy, such as a dragon.There are numerous items and weapons you can find and buy which aid you against the foes  you may encounter, from items that heal you, torches which increase your visability and charms which may freeze enemies, as well as many more. Some of these you use by using different key combinations such as down + left or up + right. Different types of weapons may have increased range, heal you if you get a certain number of kills or attack multiple enemies at once (including those positioned diagonally to you).The levels are randomly generated so there is lots of replayability, this does mean you can be screwed over on occasion depending on how certain items and enemies are spawned or not spawned, but that just adds to the fun. The soundtrack from what I've heard so far (still on Zone 1) is good, the music seems to be a kind of funky techno/trance thing, however you can set any of your own music for one or more levels. This can potentially make the game harder or easier. Enya was quite hard, but slaying enemies to the sounds of Werewolves of London by Warren Zevon was fun. As mentioned before, the level ends when the song ends so I would not recommend selecting any of the short tracks that make up the Abbey Road medley by the Beatles for example.Crypt of the NecroDancer is quite a difficult game, especially if you don't have the greatest sense of rythmn. It can be quite easy to die especially if a dragon appears and you're just armed with the starting dagger, but despite dying often, this does not give me the desire to rage quit but rather just to try again and I still find it fun. So despite being hard, for me personally this isn't a bad thing.TLDR:I recommend this game+ Fun, easy to understand which you can+ Funky music as well as the ability to use your own+ Randomly generated levels so you can repeat the same levels time and time again and each time it'll be different+ A good number of characters you can unlock+ Lots of items and weapons you can find and buy, as well as upgrades- Quite hard, I must say *dies again*- There doesn't seem to be a huge number of levels in total"
