,Recommended,247080,11490277,"Posted: 31 July, 2014",all,Sinthrex,"It's reasonable to feel skeptical about buying into an unfinished game, but if the rhythm genre floats your boat then you're more than likely going to be pleased with this one. Crypt of the NecroDancer has really simple gameplay mechanics that can get you hooked fast. The difficulty, however, is anything but simple, and therein lies the charm of this game.The tutorial does a really good job of getting you into gameplay rather quickly while laying out the rules of how to play. Everything, including you, moves to the rhythm of the music, and you study the movement patterns of your enemies to find the proper methods of eliminating them. The objective of the game becomes clear in an instant and before you know it, you're already playing. In my experience that was within the first minute. There aren't many games these days that can pull all of that off successfully, and considering this is still an alpha build I find that to be impressive.If there's anything I don't like about this game, it's that controller support isn't all there just yet. You can use a controller just fine for gameplay, but navigating the UI is another story -- I haven't been able to do anything beyond scrolling through options, so it's a little weird to switch to a keyboard in order to make selections. Nonetheless, this is a pretty trivial complaint and is only going to be improved at some point in the development cycle. At least it allows for DirectInput controllers, so if you've been deliberately avoiding using an Xbox controller and have no desire to use 3rd party programs to emulate XInput then you still have other options.Crypt of the NecroDancer has made me love the rhythm genre of games all over again, and I can see myself logging a ton of hours on it. I strongly recommend buying this game."
