76561198025178701,Recommended,247080,16698831,"Posted: 25 June, 2015",all,prometheus,"You ever been listening to music while walking down the street and subconsciously (or consciously, I don't judge) timed your steps to the beat of the music?Crypt of the Necrodancer is like that, except when you ♥♥♥♥ it up somebody stabs you and you lose your coin multiplier bonus. But that's okay, because there are about a dozen different weapons - not counting their materials modifiers, which multiplies that by six - that you can use to just stab them right back.Four zones, each with their own surprises and mechanics, enemies with varied movement patterns that make the game feel like chess on a really short timer, really ♥♥♥♥♥in' awesome music, and a shopkeeper who sings along to it! ON TOP OF THAT, there are a few reasons to try and replay the game, including more story and unlockable characters.  I mean, you know, if replaying it for the sake of playing it wasn't enough.Oh yeah, and if you get sick of the music (pfft) you can add your own music. Add some metal, give yourself a heart attack, it's great fun!Honestly, I'd recommend this game to anyone and everyone who would listen. It's that good. If you're on the fence, get it. If you like roguelikes, get it. If you like rhythm games, get it. If you like both roguelikes and rhythm games, for the love of god, GET IT."
76561198019783119,Recommended,247080,16955517,"Posted: 9 July, 2015",all,Evil Sandwich,"Ever wanted to play Dance Dance Revolution but with a bit of action and narrative added to the mix? Well Crypt of the Necrodancer is a good waltz in the right direction! Crypt of the Necrodancer is a rhythm, rogue-like dungeon crawler that has you moving and attacking to the beat of the tune.The gameplay as stated above generally has you doing everything to the beat of the tune by using only the arrow keys, whether your in the main lobby or fighting your way through the next level. You can even set the game up to be played with a dance pad! In the main lobby you're able to buy permanent upgrades to weapons, armor, spells and trinkets found in the levels,  practice against certain enemies, read background about the game and choose which zones you'll be ""dancing"" through along with a few other options. In the zones themselves the overall objective is to find the stairwell to the next level, however that doesn't necessarily mean you should be racing for the stairwell with all due haste. Diamonds, your currency for permanent upgrades, can only be found while exploring these levels, and once you are done with a zone you will only have those diamonds in your next trip to the lobby. Once you decide to go back into a zone you will lose all the diamonds you collected on the previous trip! So finding enough diamonds to buy those ever increasingly costing upgrades can be well worth the exploration. Remember how I said those permanent upgrades to items only affect what you find in the levels and are not given to the characters themselves? Those items can either be found throughout said levels or in the shop in each level. Enemies drop gold in order for you to purchase these items from the store, and if you keep up with the beat, a coin multiplier is added when you kill enemies so you get more gold for your kills. With that being said the levels are on a time limit, can you guess what that time limit is? The music! If the music you are playing to finishes before you get to the stairs you are immediately dropped to the next level. On top of this each level has a boss, and not only will you lose your multiplier combo if the song ends but rather than being dropped into a relatively safe room at the beginning of the next level you will have to face that levels boss immediately if the previous levels boss wasn't defeated.The games uses pixel art and uses it's musical theme in some of the enemy designs. For example the Minotaur enemy's  horns are actually a harp and the reaper has a microphone attached to his scythe. This leads to a very visually pleasing themed art style that looks and plays it's part.The music is electronic and catchy, even making you want to stay on a level just to keep listening. In lower levels of each zone the beat is actually slower so that players adjust to the beat as it get faster with each level.Crypt of the Necrodancer is a fun and enchanting game and is well worth your time and if you have a love for rhythm and rogue-like games alike, this original gem will not disappoint you."
,Recommended,247080,24398899,"Posted: 18 July, 2016",all,Roricorio,"This game is an absolute delight! I'd heard good things about it before purchasing it, but I had no idea just how much I would come to enjoy it until finally playing it.I was unfamiliar with the roguelike genre until Crypt of the NecroDancer, but this game totally hooked me with the concept. It gives things an interesting replay value every time you pick it up, and the variety of items and playstyles/characters give it a lot of depth. The soundtrack alone hooked me when I first heard it, and if anything, I'd highly recommend it for the tunes at the very least.It's challenging, and the learning curve from the first zone to the others is steep at times, but you can try again immediately should you die so the frustration doesn't get too overwhelming. Be careful with this game, though--it's definitely addicting!100000/10, will necrodance to my own grave and beyond."
