,Not Recommended,247080,33771171,Posted: 24 July,all,malaisling,"The quality of the game is a series of trade-offs.The animation and art for the game itself isn't particularly impressive; but it has a phenomenal soundtrack.The combat is simplistic and primitive; but innovative in a very humble way.There are plenty of items and equipment to find and unlock; but they aren't very exciting nor is the unlock system itself.The world design is quite generic fantasy babble; but it has some neat pun based silly bosses.There are a decent amount of unique areas and everything is randomized; but the map and enemy layout is inconsequential.The primary downside to the game that is not balanced out by something, like with so many games now, is the difficulty.The game has no problem with allowing chance to lock players into a deadly situation just because the enemy patterns synced up just right to be indomitable. The game has no problem with just spamming the player with enemies, which are almost impossible to survive because the player is locked to the beat and thus has a limited scope of what they can do at a time against multiple threats. Some enemies just outright have obnoxious attack patterns which require the player to literally stop everything and perform a specific chore to counter that one enemy; this being extremely problematic if that enemy has any help at the moment which the aforementioned issue of spamming enemies stacks onto. Finally, there are some enemies that literally just end the run if they show up because they are so strong and require you to do one specific thing to fight them; if you are in the wrong situation or do not have that enemy completely memorized then you just lose; because screw you for playing the game.This all massively ramps up by the third area, which is where the game completely stops caring about being reasonable and expects you to trial-and-error master memorize everything if you want to progress.Another issue is that because the attack and move buttons are the same, if the player has a weapon that hits more then just their directly adjacent tile; when the player goes to move to an open tile but something is in their weapon range in that direction they will be forced to attack it instead of moving. Which can cause legitimate problems and actual deaths. So having any weapons other then the basic one-tile-of-range dagger is also a bad thing because the way the game functions can lead to the extra range making the player attack things they don't want to, which keeps them standing still, which can get them hurt or killed. It is borderline impossible to account for in the heat of gameplay because of how awkward and unintuitive it is and thus it is just a problem that has to be accepted will hinder the player when using any weapon type except one.The minibosses aren't very balanced either, at all. Some of them are trivial, some are average, and some are ridiculously overpowered and have an eighty percent chance to just end that run the moment they show up because they are literally that absurd to fight.And the controls are quite bad. Everything is controlled by only four keys. So in a game that is meant to be rythme based and thus needs to be smooth, they thought it'd be clever to map over eight controls to four keys by requiring players to press awkward and unintuitive button combinations of those four keys to use things like healing items and spells. Not only did they make the controls bad for working with something that the player needs to do quickly if they're at low health or are in the actual spot to cast the spell and need to; they did it in a game where they have to do everything to the beat. Furthermore, the control remapping interface does not tell you what button combination does what in-game. So you have to look that up yourself. And the controller support doesn't acknowledge all the buttons on the controller, so the player can't even make use of them all which makes it harder to remap the bad controls into something playable if the player happens to prefer controllers. And using the analog stick causes the menus to flip out as well.Although the game itself has a great concept, the game almost exclusively relies on artificial difficulty. If the bad and counter-intuitive controls aren't horrible enough, the difficulty of the enemies themselves is entirely based on unfairness. The game spams the player with enemies and ganks, the game makes the player fight enemies with tedious gimmicks that require the player to stop everything just to satisfy that gimmick, the game spams players with gimmick enemies which together cause mandatory damage; because their gimmicks line up in the exact way where the player can't avoid harm or they just can't respond to everything at once, the game spams the player with environmental hazards ontop of making them fight at the same time, the game spawns enemies with gimmicks that the player may not even be able to respond to in their current setting because there isn't enough space or time to do it.The enemies themselves are almost all easy to fight, the game is difficult exclusively because it piles on enemies, hazards and blockages at once with no mercy or limitation. It expects the players to dance around it all exactly; exactly everytime to the most L33T degree in order to survive in the middle of a real time game where your movement is locked to a rythme. Even while knowing every gimmick and hazard, accounting for them all at once is absurdly difficult if not impossible. And beyond this, the game can line the player into a scenario where they fundamentally cannot survive no matter what they do. Because it is all randomly generated with no restriction, so it is possible for the player to get a game over because they were locked into an impossible situation.The final zone boss and final boss are also just, the developers just throwing in as much difficulty as they possibly can to kill the player off. The final zone boss is absurdly spam-based and expects the players to fight multiple mini bosses while the invincible boss is spam rushing them, then players have to bait the invincible boss into performing a certain action while he rapidly spam rushes at the player the moment they are in his sight and he hits for over half the players health each time if it lands. Immediately afterwards players must then fight the final boss, which requires player to juggle an absurdly overbearing gimmick while fighting off constant waves of enemies who hinder the players ability to satisfy the gimmick. Until then the final boss shows up then the final boss must be fought while still juggling this gimmick and fighting constant waves of enemies and a mini boss spawns each time you even hit the final boss. It is just the developers making as much of a stupidly overpowered end to the game as they can so players can't finish the game and thus have to keep playing.Everything about the game itself save for the controls is generally just fine. It's the completely arbitrary and meaningless sense of difficulty that the game has which makes it really hard to complement. Because there is no structure, limitation, or sense to any of it. Although during the first two biomes it isn't very significant, the final two are entirely steeped in it.It's not like in most Rogue-likes where trial and error eventually leads to the player fairing better in surviving. From start to finish it is exclusively about the random generation of the game. Either surviving because the random generation didn't just game over the playthrough, or surviving because the random generation spawned enough good items for it to not matter."
