76561198030367984,Not Recommended,247080,17936841,"Posted: 7 September, 2015",all,ExaltedDuck,"Interesting game.  It's essentially a Zork-style dungeon crawler with SNES-tribute graphics and the contraint that all movements are made in time to the music.  I bought it back when it only had two or three worlds and characters, and play it every once in a while.  The monsters get far more difficult as the game goes on but that's expected.  If the whole game were a little more like the first level, I'd recommend it.  But worlds two and three really drop the ball on art style and the music in world 2 (specifically 2-2) is completely inappropriate for a game like this, and the patterns to the monsters in the late game miss the mark for me, falling more toward frustrating challenge rather than fun challenge.  (And I really hate to rip on the music, as it is all amazing in its own right.  It's just that in places, for a beat-driven game, long strings of dotted-eight rhythms and/or spacy sweeping chords sans rhythm really don't communicate the pulse well enough)"
