76561198020319382,Recommended,247080,17530222,"Posted: 13 August, 2015",all,Tomboyo,"Crypt of the Necrodancer is quite possibly the most welcome outcome that could result from mashing together the bits and bobs of classic Rogue-likes, retro electronic beats, and rhythmic gameplay. While the notion of combining Rogue-likes (the poster-children of slow, careful deliberation) with rhythmic gameplay (which espouses just about everythingnotthe aforementioned) may seem bewilderinglymad, rest assured: Crypt of the Necrodancer seemlessly combines rhythmic mechanics with combat, exploration, planning, anddying horribly, repeatedly.I mean this in the best possible sense; after all, a core feature of Rogue-likes is repeatedly slamming head-first into opposing walls until learning of their wonderfuldoors. Necrodancer manages to let players learn about the dungeon and its rules, master the mechanics of the various enemies sprinkled lovingly throughout its midst, and still inevitably die by tripping over a particulary pernicious Green Slime without it ever becoming irritating or even remotely un-fun. The gameplay is tight, the mechanics are solid, the game is stable, there is a suprising amount of content and replayability, there are several game modes available (including the venerable Bard, which lets the player ignore the rhythm mechanics and is wonderful for learning the game), and the game has more artistic merits than a troop of Boy Scouts pledged to Bob Ross. There are no happy trees, however. The walls will literally eat you, actually, so the Bob Ross metaphore doesn't go far.Tl;Dr: The skeletonsdance.Is this not what you came for? Are you not entertained?"
