,Recommended,247080,15228697,"Posted: 5 April, 2015",all,hot n spicy,"Crypt of the NecroDancer (CotND)Crypt of the Necrodancer is a rhythm-based roguelike game featuring a unique movement mechanic based on the beat of the music. That's essentially it... even though it's a basic premise, the incredibly talented people who created this game were able to pull it off so well and make the experience of playing the game enjoyable for hours and hours.If you didn't know already, your character, who by default is Cadence, can only move to the beat of the music. If you successfully kill lots of monsters without getting hurt or messing up your movement by not moving to the beat, you get a coin multiplier that allows you to earn more coins whilst killing monsters. The coins can be used to buy stuff from a merchant to help you not die. You can also get gems to buy permanent upgrades.The graphics consist of a lot of pixel art. It looks pretty nice to me, but I've seen some people complain about the ""placeholder textures"" that are used. Which is ridiculous, because   a) they really unnoticable   and    b)IT'S AN EARLY ACCESS GAME! OF COURSE IT'S N0T COMPLETELY FINISHED!There really isn't much of a story, but it suffices for a roguelike title. Basically, this girl Cadence wants to rescue her father, who is trapped in the Crypt of the NecroDancer. Also, there's this guy Eli, who doesn't want her to go there. (Which is probably a good idea, because you will die a LOT. More on that later) The end. That's the storyline. Now I want to get to the gameplay.The gameplay is simple but very addicting. You start with a tiny dagger, and you can get a variety of weapons like the broadsword, rifle, cat o' nine tails, etc. You use these items to kill monsters like spooky scary skeletons and slimes. Like you, these monsters have to move to the beat of the music, and they follow a certain pattern. The patterns start out simply, like with the blue slime, who moves from side to side, to the goblin (this guy is such an jerk... seriously) who only follows you when your back is turned; a lot like Boos from the Mario games. The pacing is terrific: there are 3 main levels, (the 4th one is in development) and when you reach each one, there are new monsters that you have to learn the pattern of. There's also a boss at the end of each level. It's basically an incredibly fast-paced realtime strategy game, and it gets to be really difficult once you get to the 3rd level.A lot of the games greatness comes from the soundtrack.J   E   S   U   S      C   H   R   I   S   T   !The music is AMAZING. It is certainly one of the best I have ever heard. The gameplay and the music combine perfectly, making for an amazing and unique experience unlike anything you have ever heard. It's perfect in EVERY WAY. There's really nothing else to be said about the soundtrack. It's great-- you have to play the game with the music to fully appreciate it, though.Since the game is early access and still in development, there were a couple things I didn't really enjoy.  First of all, in the 3rd level, the enemies can easily swarm you. Yes, I know it's supposed to be difficult, but when you literally spawn in a mosh pit of monsters there is literally no chance for you to live. None. And there were a couple glitches when pausing. But these things really don't take away from the overall great experience the game has to offer.The game is still in-dev, but I would still buy it if it wasn't. It truly is and will evolve into an amazing game, and I can't wait to see what the developers will add on to it in the future. BUY THIS GAME!Crypt of the NecroDancer gets a 9.3 out of 10."
,Recommended,247080,15907944,"Posted: 19 May, 2015",all,bubinski,"this is honestly one of the best dungeon crawlers ive EVER played, the soundtrack is absolutely stunning, and the gameplay is fun and addictive. now go deliver those beatdowns to the beat."
76561198068277478,Recommended,247080,15910320,"Posted: 19 May, 2015",all,Dudemanguy,This game is a great example of combining the rhythm genre into other types of games. The soundtrack is great and the gameplay is difficult yet rewarding. Just what you want in a roguelike experience.-10/10 IGN
,Recommended,247080,15910836,"Posted: 19 May, 2015",all,JDRPG,"This game is fantastic. I'll admit, I love roguelike games. They are probably my favorite genre of games. I'm not so much a fan of Rhythm games, but this puts both of them together. There's only 12 levels and 6 different bosses, but that doesn't mean the content ever runs dry. I got this for sale during early access, but I would buy the game in full now. It's a steal."
76561198034476979,Recommended,247080,15911005,"Posted: 20 May, 2015",all,Lyxalot,Best Game in Existence! :D
76561198060219701,Recommended,247080,15913762,"Posted: 20 May, 2015",all,lostcraft,"One of the most insane combinations of genres I have ever played. Roguelikes focus on patience, careful thinking, and slow buildup of a character. Rhythm games focus on getting a sound pattern down. Marry those genres and you get a twitch-action game where each decision is more or less based on gut-feeling and thinking-on-your-feet.And it's awesome.As Cadence, a young woman who had her heart ripped out by the titular NecroDancer, you're bound to make it through a dungeon on a quest for answers. You're also bound to the beat. You move around a tile-based, randomly generated dungeon floor, killing monsters for gold and items, always looking for better stuff. Each level's exit is guarded by a miniboss you need to defeat in order to go deeper. So far, so rogue-light. But each level also challenges you to keep in rhythm with the background music- if you try to move outside the beat, your actions fail. And as you stay in the groove and don't take damage, a multiplier builds up that affects anything from the amount of gold an enemy earns you to the damage your weapon does. It's all really simple but also very clever (and hilarious).Enemies all have their own movement patters, also based on the beat- some, like bats, are simple and straightforward, others take a while to figure out, and then you have to adapt and react and eventually reach that blissful nirvana where you truly dance through the dungeon like an armor-clad, broadsword-wielding, bomb-throwing, spell-casting ballerina of death. Until something kills you. Then you die, and your perma-death is only softened by diamonds you picked up to purchase new items to spawn on your next run, or to unlock training areas or get some random, better, starting equipment.COTN plays very well. There's never any hiccup and every keypress gets and instant response. It also looks pretty cool, with decidedly simple pixel graphics and charming small animations everywhere. And it sounds amazing: The soundtrack alone adds ten points of awesome to the game.And it's a hard game. With four stages, each consisting of three levels and a final ""boss"" arena, a perfect run would maybe take you under an hour, but don't expect to get that perfect run anytime soon. There are lots of obstacles and the learning curve can be steep- the basics are easy to grasp but by the time moving to a constant beat and taking out the smaller mons, the game will throw you a curveball with a new pattern, a beat that changes speed, or unlockable characters with their own unique restrictions and abilities. How about a pacifist who can never deal damage? A miner who only uses bombs? A character unable to miss even one beat without dying? You name it, it's there.There's even a small story to tie the cast together and to give the whole dungeon-dancing a purpose, but to unlock it all, I was told, you need to play the game with several different characters. That'll take me a while :DIn short, this is a keeper. There's just too much cool stuff here to NOT recommend the game. Get it, play it, curse your muscle memory and keep the groove."
