,Recommended,247080,13109632,"Posted: 27 November, 2014",all,Gingerbread Man,"It's unlike anything I have ever played. It's a turn based roguelike where the turns happen on the beat of the music. If you miss a beat, you don't move. Therefore, on fast songs, your actions have to be fast and you have to think more on your feet.You start out with a Dagger, where you attack an enemy if you run into them, and there are many different weapons that attack in different ways. So you can kinda choose which one best fits how you want to fight.The broadsword swings 3 tiles in front of you, whenever there is an enemy in any of those squares and hits all.The rapier weapon attacks for twice as much damage, if there is an enemy in a square ahead of you after you move (simulating a forward thrusting action). It attacks while you move basically.The whip weapon seems to hit one enemy in a 5 tile area in front of you (left to right where you are facing).I'm sure there is more than that, I haven't unlocked everything. Other equipment and spells can be picked up and used as well. As for the inventory system, there really isn't any. You run over items to equip them (previous items in the slot get dropped on the ground), and use UP+LEFT, or UP+RIGHT, etc. to use items. It makes it fast, easy, and quickly accessable.My ONLY gripe, is that it seems like a small game right now. It's in pre-alpha, and I look forward to it expanding. Everything so far about it is great. The difficulty might be a bit high for some (which really shouldn't be a complaint), but if you are like me and hate not being challenged by todays games, you will have fun with this, and you will get better at it (which again, is why it shouldn't be a complaint). The developer has my kudos for making such an unique and amazing game."
,Recommended,247080,13110164,"Posted: 27 November, 2014",all,Stripeknight,Game is freaking AWESOME!
,Recommended,247080,13095239,"Posted: 26 November, 2014",all,Flavourius,"Reason why I bought this game in the first place, was because of it's soundtrack.For every metal-fans out there, you should definetly buy this game, even if you don't like it or is a bit hard for you, just buy this for it's music."
,Recommended,247080,13095859,"Posted: 26 November, 2014",all,TheHiMan,"This game is awesome! Has a great soundtrack, it makes the best of both the rhythm genre and the rogue-like dungeon crawler genre, and amazing even though it's in early access. Just be ready for a giant learning curve after the tutorial, but after 2 runs, you'll start to get it. I've had this game for an hour, and I've played it for an hour.10/10"
,Recommended,247080,13097489,"Posted: 26 November, 2014",all,thelarchmage,"Ok, this game is unbelievable. You wouldn't think that a rhythm game/dungeon-crawler would make for an entertaining experience, but it is astoundingly addicting.As of the writing of this review, the game is still in Early Access, but the game has enough content to warrant pulling the requisite $15 from your wallet.The game is simplistic, but has great depth. The game is controlled with only four buttons; (but a d-pad won't work, as opposite directions need to be pressed at the same time) up, down, left, and right. These buttons will either move your character, or attack in the direction selected. Combinations of the four buttons are assigned to spells and items. This makes the game compatible with a USB dance pad if you so choose to play it that way. Though it lacks falling arrows, the mechanics become remarkably similar. Moving your character to the beat of the music comes suprisingly naturally, and plays out as more of an action-puzzler than anything else.Of course, no rhythm game is complete without an awesome soundtrack, and this game absolutely delivers in the auditory stimulation department. The chiptune dance tracks go perfectly with the artstyle of each floor, but do not get old as most songs do on other dance-pad games. And, if they ever do get old for you, the game offers support for adding in your own jams. The beat detection is good, but for your own sanity, pick songs that don't vary much in tempo, or you will be losing your combos.All in all, solid 10 from me. The only qualm I have with it is that the difficulty curve is fairly steep, and may be a little too much for those inexperienced with the falling arrow games arcade gamers grew up with. For those who are seeking a challenge, there is Aria mode, which is essentially a perfect-only mode."
